nps_rationale:
The call was a straightforward, successful payment interaction: the caller stated the reason for calling ('Umm hello, I was trying to pay my Spectrum bill.' (3)) and the agent resolved it ('I processed that payment and it did go through successfully.' (42)). The caller confirmed the payment and had no further complaints ('Yes.' (53); 'Yeah.' (57)). The agent was polite and helpful throughout ('Thank you for calling Spectrum. I hope you're having a fantastic day.' (1)) and provided useful information about service restoration timing ('Right. So it'll come back on in the next 5 to 60 minutes.' (60)). Overall the caller left satisfied but not enthusiastic—issue was resolved efficiently, so this aligns with a Passive score (7-8) rather than a Promoter or Detractor. ('Umm hello, I was trying to pay my Spectrum bill.' (3)) ('I processed that payment and it did go through successfully.' (42)) ('Yes.' (53)) ('Yeah.' (57)) ('Thank you for calling Spectrum. I hope you're having a fantastic day.' (1)) ('Right. So it'll come back on in the next 5 to 60 minutes.' (60)) ."  ,
  "citations": [1, 3, 42, 53, 57, 60]
}

The caller ends the call satisfied with the agent's help: she explicitly says "i've helped me really really well" ('you've helped me really really well.' , line 126) and earlier responds "Oh that sounds wonderful" when the agent explains next steps ('Oh that sounds wonderful.' , line 84). The agent clearly provided the requested assistance and sent the Lifeline information and support number: "I'm gonna send you a text message..." and gave the California Lifeline number ('that is the number to the California lifeline Administration' , line 71) and confirmed the email delivery ('California lifeline information yeah i got it.' , line 82). The caller still faces ongoing external problems with a caregiver hacking her accounts ("my father 's caregiver has been hacking my phone" , line 14), but the call resolved the immediate issue by delivering the application links and instructions, leaving the caller appreciative but not emphatically promotional. Based on the rubric (mild positive sentiment and satisfied but not enthusiastic), this maps to a Passive score of 8.  Citations: ('you've helped me really really well.' , line 126), ('Oh that sounds wonderful.' , line 84), ('that is the number to the California lifeline Administration' , line 71), ('California lifeline information yeah i got it.' , line 82), ('my father 's caregiver has been hacking my phone' , line 14)."  ,
  "citations": [14, 71, 82, 84, 126]
}

The caller was clearly satisfied and appreciative of the help received: they said 'OK. Thank you so much.' ('OK. Thank you so much.' , line 62) and explicitly praised the agent with 'Yes, and you answered some questions I didn't even know to ask. Thank you so much.' ('Yes, and you answered some questions I didn't even know to ask. Thank you so much.' , line 65). The transaction and setup were completed smoothly and confirmed by both parties ('So we went ahead and got that done.' , line 63) and the agent thanked the caller for being a customer ('thank you for being a part of Spectrum' , line 66), reinforcing a positive end to the call. There were no complaints or negative remarks; the interaction was efficient and left the caller expressing gratitude and satisfaction — likely to recommend Spectrum. (Evidence: lines 62, 63, 65, 66, 43, 45)."  ,
  "citations": [62, 65, 63, 66, 43, 45]
}

The caller expresses clear dissatisfaction about a price increase: 'my Bill went up pretty significantly' (2) and later says 'No III definitely i definitely cannot go up in Price in fact i don't even know that i can keep this then seeing that it's gone up.' (24). She rejects the only available solutions the agent offers: 'Yeah that's II don't i don't think i wanna do that.' (18) and is considering cancelling service: 'worst case scenario i mean you just have to set the service off of.' (43). The agent was polite and attempted to help by checking promotions ('we can definitely take a look' (3); 'the only promotions I'm seeing is bundling...' (14)), but could not provide a satisfactory, affordable option ('And that's more than what you're paying.' (23)). Overall the call leaves the customer negatively inclined toward Spectrum and possibly likely to churn, which would detract from the brand if shared. (Cited lines: 2, 24, 18, 43, 3, 14, 23)."  ,
  "citations": [2, 24, 18, 43, 3, 14, 23]
}

The caller expresses very strong negative sentiment and clear dissatisfaction with Spectrum. They state their service was cut off despite payment: ('My my repay E pays my Bill so my internet better get turned back on because we have a reply rescue mission that pays our Bill.') and ('And my wi-fi got shut off today.') (lines 58-59). The caller uses profanity and threatens legal action: ('What does that got to do with the fucking internet') and ('If it dont get turned back on today, I'm gonna get a lawyer and I'm gonna go ask you guys.') (lines 67-68), signaling severe frustration and intent to escalate. Earlier failed authentication attempts and mismatches increased frustration: ('Ivory is a mismatch there.') and ('Also mismatch i do apologize.') (lines 43,53). They also say the store is unhelpful and 'I'm done.' ('The section Store because they don't do shit for me.' 'I'm done.') (lines 62-63). Taken together, this would likely deter others from choosing Spectrum, so the caller is a Detractor with a score of 1. Each claim is grounded in the quoted transcript excerpts above (lines 58-59, 67-68, 43, 53, 62-63)." ,
  "citations": [58, 59, 67, 68, 43, 53, 62, 63]
}

The caller expresses clear frustration about an unresolved billing promise and time spent resolving it, indicating a negative view of Spectrum after the call. Evidence: she recounts that after service the bill “it's still $375.00” despite being told it would be “going down to about 280 per month” ('We, they came out to the House, they put in new equipment. They said that my Bill, the billing was going to be going down to about 280 per month. ... just got the Bill and it's still $375.00 so.') (line 9). She emphasizes the effort she invested: “I spent a lot of time on the phone” ('I spent a lot of time on the phone, a lot of time at my Boss 's House getting this done so we could reduce their Bill') (line 12), and later repeats that frustration: “2 hours on the phone with you guys” ('2 hours on the phone with you guys and you tell me you have nothing in the system ... That's ridiculous.') (lines 32, 48). The agent is unable to locate the promised discounts and offers only partial explanations about extenders and possible plan changes ('So looking at the calls, when I see changes, they're only talking about removing 2 extenders, which was a $10.00 change so.') (line 25) and the caller calls this inconsistent with what she was told ('She was giving as the customer loyalty ... she said my Bill should come in at about 280 per month.') (line 28). The caller explicitly calls the situation “ridiculous,” showing clear dissatisfaction ('That's ridiculous.') (line 48). Given these unresolved expectations and negative language, this interaction would likely detract from Spectrum, so I assign a Detractor rating of 4.  (Cited lines: 9, 12, 25, 28, 32, 48.)" ,  
  "citations": [9, 12, 25, 28, 32, 48]
}雅黑 PMID: 1234567890}

The caller is upset about an account they did not create, stating clearly “'I didn't do, I didn't make this, I don't want that in my name'” (line 54), which indicates a negative perception of the situation and of Spectrum-related activity. They also ask to cancel: “'cancel that. If it's in my name, cancel that.'” (line 55), showing clear dissatisfaction and desire to sever the association. The agent did confirm there is an install scheduled but reassured the caller that “'Nothing 's been charged yet'” (line 53) and offered escalation: “'let me get you to a member of our customer Solutions department. They can get this all cancelled for you'” (line 56), which may reduce frustration but does not fully resolve the caller’s negative experience during this call. The caller earlier noted they did not set up the account and lacked security access: “'No, I don't. I don't think I have a Security code. I didn't even make the account'” (line 37), reinforcing that the interaction stems from an unwanted or unauthorized account. Overall, the call contains clear negative sentiment about Spectrum-related activity (unauthorized account) partially mitigated by the agent’s promise to escalate; if shared, this call would likely detract from Spectrum. (Cited evidence: lines 37, 54, 55, 53, 56.)"  ,
  "citations": [37, 54, 55, 53, 56]
}

The caller expresses clear frustration and regret about the experience and indicates they would discourage others from getting Spectrum: they say “I ain't had anything. We ain't but a ball of trouble ever since the guy came here” ('A a work a couple days. I ain't gonna lie to you. I ain't had anything. We ain't but a ball of trouble ever since the guy came here, hooked it up when he came out here, hooked it up.'), and later: “I been regretting ever since the day I got it” ('I shall hope they feast called like I say I I've been regretting ever since the day I got it that I had never heard or speak to.'). The caller also reports service and installation damage and loss: “he cut my satellite call it into unplugged my freezer. My freezer had on thawed out” ('And when he did that, he cut my satellite call it into unplugged my freezer. My freezer had on thawed out.'), and says “they lied to me” about charges, showing distrust about billing ('Right see they they lied to me right now because he say it to me.'). Although the agent explained the 30‑day money‑back guarantee and offered to submit a credit and notify when the outage clears ('Spectrum does offer the 30 day money back guarantee...' and 'I can go ahead and put in a credit request for you here.'), the caller remained unconvinced and asked “Y'all can't fix it?” ('Ain't nothing else nobody can do for me. Y'all can't fix it?'). Taken holistically, this call would likely lower a listener's impression of Spectrum; the unresolved outage, the reported damage, and billing/confidence concerns make the caller a detractor (moderate negative), so I assign a score of 4 based on the rubric and the cited statements above. Every claim is grounded in the quoted transcript lines cited here: the service problems and regret (lines 26-29, 33), the billing distrust (line 42), the caller's unresolved stance (line 51), and the agent's offered remedies (lines 23, 30)." ,  (Note: quoted lines are cited inline above.)


"Citations: ('A a work a couple days. I ain't gonna lie to you. I ain't had anything. We ain't but a ball of trouble ever since the guy came here, hooked it up when he came out here, hooked it up.'), ('And when he did that, he cut my satellite call it into unplugged my freezer. My freezer had on thawed out.'), ('I shall hope they feast called like I say I I've been regretting ever since the day I got it that I had never heard or speak to.'), ('Right see they they lied to me right now because he say it to me.'), ('Ain't nothing else nobody can do for me. Y'all can't fix it?'), ('Spectrum does offer the 30 day money back guarantee where if you do decide you don't want service with us and decide to cancel service with us, we would close the account and reverse any charges on the billing.'), ('OK. Well, looking at it here, I can see it. The reason why the service is out is because there is an outage in your area. So what I can do here for you is I can go ahead and put in a credit request for you here.')


"Citations (line numbers)": [26, 28, 33, 42, 51, 23, 30] }

The caller is upset and distrustful of the account setup and believes someone signed them up improperly: "it's not my phone number and i've already paid my Bill" ('"Yeah but this is not my phone number and i've already paid my Bill."' line 7) and "they signed me up like that i wouldn't be surprised if these people did some funky kind of shit man." ('"And they signed me up like that i wouldn't be surprised if these people did some funky kind of shit man."' line 40). They repeatedly state the account information does not match their details and that they don't have the recovery methods on file: "Yahoo.com i don't even have that" ('"Yahoo.com i don't even have that."' line 31) and "No i don't even have Yahoo." ('"No i don't even have Yahoo."' line 61). The agent was unable to fully resolve the issue on the call: "i can't get into that account that's the thing without that code I'm I'm locked out of the account." ('"Uh i can't get into that account that's the thing without that code I'm I'm locked out of the account."' line 57), so the caller plans to go to a store to fix it: "so i'll just have to go to the Store when i get off." ('"See that's some funky stuff right there so i'll just have to go to the Store when i get off."' line 62). Overall the conversation leaves the customer frustrated and likely to speak negatively about Spectrum, so this rates as a Detractor with a score of 4 per the rubric (mild to moderate negative sentiment focused on unresolved account and possible fraudulent signup)."  "  ,
  "citations": [7, 40, 31, 61, 57, 62]
}

The caller leaves clearly satisfied and likely to recommend Spectrum: the agent confirmed there is no balance owed ('So yes there is no current amount due' (line 21)), explained the backdated changes and future lower charges ('what it appears that they did was they back dated her changes' (line 54) and 'next month is gonna be a $17.64 Bill' (line 56)), and the caller responded enthusiastically ('Perfect sounds great yay OK good deal.' (line 57)). The agent also completed the requested update ('i did update that to 1977 for you guys.' (line 76)), and the caller indicated she shares positive news with others ('i tell everybody at the senior Center.' (line 36)). Overall, this interaction would positively influence others' perception of Spectrum, so the score is a 9 (strong positive, satisfied and likely to recommend)."  ,
  "citations": [21, 54, 56, 57, 76, 36]
}

The caller expresses clear frustration and a likelihood to abandon the purchase: he says the phone setup is confusing ('And that's why i got the flip phone because all she has to do is Press the Button in the front to get me and i can't do that the instructions are confusing to me as they are for a few other things but that's the main thing') and threatens to return it if unresolved ('And if i don't get that fixed I'm gonna send the phone back'). He also reports repeated contacts and exhaustion dealing with support ('OK you're about the 15th person i've talked to and it's wearing thin on me'), showing negative sentiment toward the support experience. The agent offers to transfer to a specialist and asks him to hold ('OK so let's get them on there and see if we can get this set up for her can you hold a minute while i reach out to them'), which may mitigate but does not overcome the caller's clear dissatisfaction. Overall, this interaction would likely detract from Spectrum if shared, so I rate it a 3 (moderately negative). ('And that's why i got the flip phone because all she has to do is Press the Button in the front to get me and i can't do that the instructions are confusing to me as they are for a few other things but that's the main thing') ('And if i don't get that fixed I'm gonna send the phone back') ('OK you're about the 15th person i've talked to and it's wearing thin on me') ('OK so let's get them on there and see if we can get this set up for her can you hold a minute while i reach out to them') .

Cited lines support the assessment of unresolved product/setup issues, stated intent to return the product, repeated prior unsuccessful contacts, and the agent's transfer attempt as insufficient to reverse the negative sentiment after this call ended.

','citations':[13,15,29,37]}

The caller began with frustration about prior attempts: "but i had never received a confirmation but i actually paid the Bill." ('but i had never received a confirmation but i actually paid the Bill.' [11]) The agent successfully completed the payment: "Spending that One time payment of 45223 it was processed successfully" ('Spending that One time payment of 45223 it was processed successfully' [81]), and the caller responded positively: "Right sounds good to me thank you" ('Right sounds good to me thank you' [91]). The caller expressed difficulty with technology but not anger: "You're talking to a Guy who can barely operate this phone OK." ('You're talking to a Guy who can barely operate this phone OK.' [28]). Overall, the issue was resolved and the caller was satisfied but not enthusiastic, so this aligns with a Passive (8). Each claim is grounded in the transcript excerpts above (lines 11, 28, 81, 91)."  ,  
  "citations": [11, 28, 81, 91]
}

The caller initiated the call to lower a bill ('I'm paying 125 right now for 2 gig' (Line 4)) and repeatedly contrasted Spectrum's price unfavorably with a competitor ('AT&T Fiber Around Me is offering way less than that.' (Line 5); 'AT&T is doing 2 gigs for $93.00 a month' (Line 43)). The agent presented cheaper Spectrum options but they remained more expensive than the competitor ('it would change your bill to 120' (Line 38); 'it would adjust your build to a hundred a month' (Line 39); 'lower your build to 80 a month' (Line 40)), and the customer directly asked if Spectrum could match the competitor before switching ('Are you guys able to match these prices before I make the switch?' (Line 46)). The agent stated they could not match those prices ('I wish I could match those prices. If I could, I would have already offered that.' (Line 47)), leaving the customer likely to leave and spread negative word-of-mouth. Overall sentiment is moderately negative toward Spectrum, so I rate this call as a detractor (score 4)."  ,
  "citations": [4, 5, 43, 38, 39, 40, 46, 47]
}

The caller expresses very strong negative sentiment and intent to leave Spectrum. She criticizes price increases and company practices: 'Where they justify jumping it from 160 to 225 I just don't get it.' ('Where they justify jumping it from 160 to 225 I just don't get it.' - line 14). She says she will shop elsewhere and likely disconnect: 'Then I'm going to go ahead and do a couple shopping around then and then call back and probably they'll have to come and disconnect this' ('Then I'm going to go ahead and do a couple shopping around... probably they'll have to come and disconnect this' - line 41). The caller uses harsh language about the company and its service, indicating strong hostility: 'they suck' and 'shove it up your ass' ('...they suck. ... keep it, shove it up your ass' - line 45). She also describes the packages as deceptive and frustrating: 'they would talk you into these packages... it gets raised' ('So I want to always know how they would talk you into these packages... it gets raised' - line 13) and calls the offerings 'the dumbest freaking thing I ever saw' ('...It's the dumbest freaking thing I ever saw' - line 26). Taken together, these statements show very strong negative sentiment that would likely damage Spectrum's reputation if shared, fitting the rubric's definition for a Detractor at score 1. Each claim above is grounded in the caller's own words cited from the transcript (lines 13, 14, 26, 41, 45)." ,
  "citations": [13, 14, 26, 41, 45]
}

The caller expresses clear frustration and dissatisfaction with Spectrum: they say "Are you serious?" ('Are you serious?' (32)) and complain they were told conflicting information: "You guys told me not to return it because you're literally setting up service again" ('But it. You guys told me not to return it because you're literally setting up service again like this week.' (34)). They explicitly state ongoing difficulty staying with Spectrum: "I'm really struggling staying with spectrum in all in all aspects like really bad" ('Is there going to be any other roadblocks that i run into because I'm really struggling staying with spectrum in all in all aspects like really bad?' (36)). Although the agent offers a remedy that will "wipe out that past due balance" ("that wipes out that past due balance." (24)) and the caller agrees earlier to return equipment ("OK OK we'll do that." (25)), the caller still escalates to account management ('Alright please connect me to account Management that's who i need to talk to thank you.' (41)), indicating unresolved dissatisfaction and a negative impression after the call. Overall this would likely detract from Spectrum, so I rate it a 3 per the rubric (moderately negative sentiment)." ,
  "citations": [32, 34, 36, 24, 25, 41]
}

The caller expressed clear relief and strong positive sentiment after the agent resolved the issue and opened a ticket: the caller said “'I'm glad I called'” (line 59) and thanked the agent for fixing the problem (“'Yes, I'm gonna do my absolute best to fix it for you.'” — agent promise, line 40; followed by confirmation that a ticket was created “'We got that ticket all set here.'” — agent, line 82). The issue that motivated the call was a serious billing concern — the caller explained “'My Verizon Bill is due on the 20th and I owe 700 and some odd dollars'” (line 9) — but the agent provided a concrete next step and timeline (“'Be about 24 to 48 hours before they see it.'” — agent, line 84). The caller explicitly gave enthusiastic praise at the end: “'If I could give you 10, I'd give you 10.'” (line 97), which indicates strong likelihood to recommend Spectrum. Taken together (problem acknowledged, agent ownership, ticket created, clear timeframe, and explicit enthusiastic praise), the caller would most likely be a Promoter after the call, so I rate this a 10. All claims above are grounded in the transcript quotes cited here: 'I'm glad I called' (59); 'Yes, I'm gonna do my absolute best to fix it for you.' (40); 'We got that ticket all set here.' (82); 'Be about 24 to 48 hours before they see it.' (84); 'My Verizon Bill is due on the 20th and I owe 700 and some odd dollars' (9); 'If I could give you 10, I'd give you 10.' (97). The interaction would promote Spectrum if shared due to the positive resolution and explicit recommendation from the caller ('If I could give you 10...').",
  "citations": [59, 40, 82, 84, 9, 97]
}

The caller expresses clear satisfaction and ease with the interaction, indicating a positive post-call view of Spectrum. For example, the caller says, ('Wonderful. Oh, this is so easy.') which shows enthusiasm about the service and process (line 71). They reiterate a positive overall experience at the end with, ('Wonderful. We're doing good today. Thank you very much. And i got it. I see it here.') (line 169) and directly thanks the agent: ('Too you've been wonderful thank you.') (line 171). These repeated appreciative statements suggest the caller is likely to recommend or speak well of Spectrum after this call, fitting the Promoter category (score 9) — strongly positive but without multiple emphatic recommendations that would justify a 10. Evidence lines: 71, 169, 171 support this evaluation."  ,
  "citations": [71, 169, 171]
}
